{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "Recent results from OKA setup concerning form factor studies in K e3 decay are presented. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "About 5.25M events are selected for the analysis. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The linear and quadratic slopes for the decay formfactor f + (t) are measured: \u03bb \u2032 + = (26.1\u00b10.35\u00b10.28)\u00d710 \u22123 , \u03bb \u2032\u2032 + = (1.91\u00b10.19\u00b10.14)\u00d710 \u22123 . ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The scalar and tensor contributions are compatible with zero. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "Several alternative parametrizations are tried: the Pole fit parameter is found to be M V = 891 \u00b1 2.0 MeV ; the parameter of the Dispersive parametrization is measured to be \u039b + = (24.58 \u00b1 0.18) \u00d7 10 \u22123 . ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The presented results are considered as preliminary.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The kaon decays provide unique information about the dynamics of the strong interactions. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "It has been a testing ground for such theories as current algebra, PCAC, Chiral Perturbation Theory (ChPT) etc. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Another direction is a search for new interactions, such as tensor and scalar ones. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Here, we present a high-statistics study of K e3 decays from OKA detector at U-70 Proton Synchrotron.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "OKA beam and detector",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "OKA is the abbreviation for \u2032 Experiments with Kaons \u2032 . ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "OKA beam is a RF-separated secondary beam of U-70 Proton Synchrotron of IHEP, Protvino. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The beam is described elsewhere [1]. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 32,
                    "end": 35,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "RF-separation with Panofsky scheme is realised. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "It uses two superconductive Karsruhe-CERN SC RF deflectors [2], donated by CERN. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 59,
                    "end": 62,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "[2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Sophisticated cryogenic system, built at IHEP [3] provides superfluid He for cavities cooling. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 46,
                    "end": 49,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The resulting beam has up to \u223c 20% of kaons with an intensity of \u223c 10 6 kaons per 3 sec U-70 spill. ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The OKA  ",
            "section": "OKA beam and detector",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Trigger and statistics",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Very simple trigger, which is almost \u2032\u2032 minimum bias \u2032\u2032 one, has been used during datataking:",
            "section": "Trigger and statistics",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "It is a combination of beam Sc counters, C 1,2 threshold Cerenkov counters (\u010c 1 sees pions,\u010c 2 -pions and kaons), S bk -a \u2032\u2032 beam-killer \u2032\u2032 counter located in the beam-hole of the GAMS gamma-detector. ",
            "section": "Trigger and statistics",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 180,
                    "end": 184,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "GAMS",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u03a3 GAM S > MIP is a requirement for the analog sum of amplitudes in the GAMS-2000 to be higher than a MIP signal. ",
            "section": "Trigger and statistics",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 71,
                    "end": 75,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "GAMS",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u2032\u2032 OKA \u2032\u2032 is taking data since 2010, the total available statistics corresponds to \u223c 15MK e3 decays. ",
            "section": "Trigger and statistics",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "In the present study we use part of the statistics taken in 2012 and 2013.",
            "section": "Trigger and statistics",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "K e3 decay study.",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The data processing starts with the beam particle reconstruction in BP C 1 \u00f7 BP C 4 , then the secondary tracks are looked for in P C 1 \u00f7 P C 8 ; ST 1 \u00f7 ST 3 ; DT 1 \u00f7 DT 2 and events with one good positive track are selected. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The decay vertex is searched for, and a cut is introduced on the matching of incoming and decay track. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The next step is to look for showers in GAMS-2000 and EGS calorimeters. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 40,
                    "end": 44,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "GAMS",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The electron identification is done using the ratio of the energy of the shower to the momentum of the associated track. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The E/p distribution is shown in Fig. 2. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 33,
                    "end": 39,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The particles with 0.8 < E/p < 1.2 are accepted as electrons. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The events with one charged track identified as electron and two additional showers in ECAL are selected for further processing. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The mass spectrum of \u03b3\u03b3 shows a clean \u03c0 0 peak at M \u03c00 = 134.9 MeV with a resolution of \u223c 8.5 MeV. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 63,
                    "end": 66,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "MeV",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w3"
                },
                {
                    "start": 94,
                    "end": 97,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "MeV",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "To fight the main background from K \u03c02 decay, the angle between the momentum of the beam kaon p K and that of the e\u03c0-system i.e. p e + p \u03c0 is considered, see Fig. 2. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 158,
                    "end": 164,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The background is clearly seen as a peak at zero angles. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The cut is \u03b1 > 1.6 mrad. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Further selection is done by the requirement that the event passes 2C K \u2192 e\u03bd\u03c0 0 fit. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The event selection results in \u223c5.25M events. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The surviving background is estimated from MC to be less than 1%. ",
            "section": "K e3 decay study.",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Analysis",
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The analysis is based on the fit of the distribution of the events over the Dalitz plot. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The variables y = 2E * e /M K and z = 2E * \u03c0 /M K , where E * e , E * \u03c0 are the energies of the electron and \u03c0 0 in the kaon c.m.s are used. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The background events, as MC shows, occupy the peripheral part of the plot. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The most general Lorentz invariant form of the matrix element for the decay K + \u2192 l + \u03bd\u03c0 0 is [4]:",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 94,
                    "end": 97,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It consists of vector, scalar and tensor terms. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "f \u00b1 are the functions of t = (P K \u2212 P \u03c0 ) 2 . ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "In the Standard Model (SM) the W-boson exchange leads to the pure vector term. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The term in the vector part, proportional to f \u2212 is reduced(using the Dirac equation) to a scalar form-factor, proportional to (m l /2m K )f \u2212 and is negligible in the case of K e3 . ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 70,
                    "end": 75,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Dirac",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Different parametrizations have been used for f + (t). ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "First is just a Taylor series:",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": ". It is usually used to compare with ChPT predictions. Alternative parametrization is the pole one:",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The last is a relatively new Dispersive parametrization [5]:",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 56,
                    "end": 59,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Here H(t) is a known function. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The procedure for the experimental extraction of the parameters \u03bb + , f S , f T , which was developed in [6] is used. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 105,
                    "end": 108,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This procedure allows avoiding systematic errors due to the \"migration\" of the events over the Dalitz plot because of the finite experimental resolution. ",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The radiative corrections were taken into account by reweighting every MC event, according to [7].",
            "section": "Analysis",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 94,
                    "end": 97,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The fit with linear parametrization of the form factor gives \u03bb + = (2.95 \u00b10.022) \u00d710 \u22122 . ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "It could be compared to quite old ChP T O(p 4 ) result [8]:",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 55,
                    "end": 58,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The results of the fits are summarized in Table 1. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 42,
                    "end": 49,
                    "type": "table",
                    "ref_id": "tab_1",
                    "text": "Table 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The first line is the \"standard \u2032\u2032 fit with two parameters -linear and quadratic slopes. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The quadratic term is quite significant, there is a strong correlation between parameters as it is seen in Fig. 3. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 107,
                    "end": 113,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The quality of the fit is illustrated by the z projection of the Dalitz plot, shown on is the points with errors; histogram is the fit, corresponding to the first line of the Table 1.",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 175,
                    "end": 182,
                    "type": "table",
                    "ref_id": "tab_1",
                    "text": "Table 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "respectively. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Next lines represent the quadratic, Pole and Dispersive fits with additional tensor and scalar contributions. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "It is seen, that f S and f T are not significant. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The main contribution to systematic is coming from the variation of the cut on Z coordinate of the vertex and the cut on the angle \u03b1. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The contributions to the systematic errors from Z and \u03b1 variations are (0.021, 0.014) \u2022 10 \u22122 and (0.11, 0.06) \u2022 10 \u22123 for \u03bb \u2032 + and \u03bb \u2032\u2032 + respectively. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Finally, we get the results for the quadratic fit: \u03bb \u2032 + = (2.611 \u00b1 0.035 \u00b1 0.028) \u2022 10 \u22122 and \u03bb \u2032\u2032 + = (1.91 +0.19 \u22120.18 \u00b1 0.14) \u2022 10 \u22123 . ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The result of the Pole fit can be compared to the PDG value for the K * mass [9]: M K * = 891.66 \u00b1 0.26 MeV. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 77,
                    "end": 80,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[9]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 104,
                    "end": 107,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "MeV",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w6"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "An interpretation of limits on F S and F T is possible in the framework of the scalar LeptoQuark(LQ) model. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Then a diagram with LQ exchange should be added to the SM diagram with W. Applying Fiertz transformation to the LQ matrix element we get: (s\u00b5)(\u03bdu) = \u2212 1 2 (su)(\u03bd\u00b5) \u2212 1 8 (s\u03c3 \u03b1\u03b2 u)(\u03bd\u03c3 \u03b1\u03b2 \u00b5). ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The first term is the scalar, the second one -tensor. ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The relation between f S , f T and the Leptoquark scale \u039b LQ can be set out ( [10]). ",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 78,
                    "end": 82,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "As a result, a 95% lower limit for the LeptoQuark scale is \u039b LQ > 3.5 TeV.",
            "section": "Results and comparison with theory",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
